y="n"><svg viewBox="0 0 1000 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m250 850l-187 0-63 0 0-62 0-188 63 0 0 188 187 0 0 62z m688 0l-188 0 0-62 188 0 0-188 62 0 0 188 0 62-62 0z m-875-938l0 188-63 0 0-188 0-62 63 0 187 0 0 62-187 0z m875 188l0-188-188 0 0-62 188 0 62 0 0 62 0 188-62 0z m-125 188l-1 0-93-94-156 156 156 156 92-93 2 0 0 250-250 0 0-2 93-92-156-156-156 156 94 92 0 2-250 0 0-250 0 0 93 93 157-156-157-156-93 94 0 0 0-250 250 0 0 0-94 93 156 157 156-157-93-93 0 0 250 0 0 250z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a></div><div class="modebar-group"><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn" data-title="Show closest data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="closest" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1500 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m375 725l0 0-375-375 375-374 0-1 1125 0 0 750-1125 0z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a><a rel="tooltip" class="modebar-btn active" data-title="Compare data on hover" data-attr="hovermode" data-val="x" data-toggle="false" data-gravity="ne"><svg viewBox="0 0 1125 1000" class="icon" height="1em" width="1em"><path d="m187 786l0 2-187-188 188-187 0 0 937 0 0 373-938 0z m0-499l0 1-187-188 188-188 0 0 937 0 0 376-938-1z" transform="matrix(1 0 0 -1 0 850)"></path></svg></a></div></div></div><svg class="main-svg" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="348.33333333333337" height="378.33333333333337"><g class="hoverlayer"></g></svg></div></div></div></foreignObject></g><text class="draggable" name="text" x="210" y="22" r="0" rtemp="0" transform="rotate(0 210  22)" style="fill: rgb(255, 123, 0); font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-size: 13px; font-family: normal;">out</text><text class="draggable" name="text" x="84" y="21" r="0" rtemp="0" transform="rotate(0 84  21)" style="fill: rgb(255, 123, 0); font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-size: 13px; font-family: normal;">in</text><g transform="translate(328,17)" x="328" y="17" title="codeHTML" width="427" height="384" class="codeHTML" name="codeHTML" rot="0"><foreignObject x="0" y="0" width="222" height="200" style="height: 640px; width: 711.667px;"><div name="htmlCode" style="zoom: 60%; height: 640px; width: 711.667px;" code="<div class=&quot;ch&quot;>
    
    <h1>RC High-Pass Filter - SPICE AC Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Capacitor (C1):</strong> 1 &amp;micro;F (in series with input)</li>
            <li><strong>Resistor (R1):</strong> 1 k&amp;Omega; (to ground)</li>
            <li><strong>Input (V1):</strong> AC Voltage Source (1V amplitude)</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> Taken across resistor R1</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Cutoff Frequency</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        fc = 1 / (2&amp;pi;RC) = 1 / (2&amp;pi; &amp;times; 1000 &amp;times; 1&amp;times;10&amp;minus;6) &amp;approx; <strong>159 Hz</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Magnitude Response (Black Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stop Band:</strong> Strong attenuation for f &amp;lt; 159 Hz</li>
                <li>At 1 Hz: attenuation &amp;approx; -40 dB</li>
                <li><strong>Cutoff Point:</strong> -3 dB at 159 Hz</li>
                <li><strong>Pass Band:</strong> 0 dB gain for f &amp;gt; 1 kHz</li>
                <li>Slope: +20 dB/decade in stop band</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Phase Response (Red Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Low Freq:</strong> +90&amp;deg; (+1.57 rad) phase lead</li>
                <li><strong>At Cutoff (fc):</strong> +45&amp;deg; (+0.785 rad)</li>
                <li><strong>High Freq:</strong> Approaches 0&amp;deg; (0 rad)</li>
                <li>Capacitor causes leading phase at low frequencies</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>The circuit functions as a <strong>high-pass filter</strong>. It blocks low-frequency signals (below 159 Hz) with significant attenuation while allowing high-frequency signals to pass through with minimal loss. The capacitor blocks DC and low frequencies, while passing AC signals above the cutoff frequency. The phase leads at low frequencies and approaches zero at high frequencies.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>Key Differences from Low-Pass Filter</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Component arrangement:</strong> C in series, R to ground (reversed from LPF)</li>
            <li><strong>Frequency response:</strong> Passes HIGH frequencies, blocks LOW frequencies</li>
            <li><strong>Magnitude slope:</strong> +20 dB/decade (rising) vs -20 dB/decade (falling)</li>
            <li><strong>Phase:</strong> Starts at +90&amp;deg; and goes to 0&amp;deg; (vs 0&amp;deg; to -90&amp;deg; for LPF)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>"><div class="ch">
    
    <h1>RC High-Pass Filter - SPICE AC Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Capacitor (C1):</strong> 1 µF (in series with input)</li>
            <li><strong>Resistor (R1):</strong> 1 kΩ (to ground)</li>
            <li><strong>Input (V1):</strong> AC Voltage Source (1V amplitude)</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> Taken across resistor R1</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Cutoff Frequency</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        fc = 1 / (2πRC) = 1 / (2π × 1000 × 1×10−6) ≈ <strong>159 Hz</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Magnitude Response (Black Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stop Band:</strong> Strong attenuation for f &lt; 159 Hz</li>
                <li>At 1 Hz: attenuation ≈ -40 dB</li>
                <li><strong>Cutoff Point:</strong> -3 dB at 159 Hz</li>
                <li><strong>Pass Band:</strong> 0 dB gain for f &gt; 1 kHz</li>
                <li>Slope: +20 dB/decade in stop band</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Phase Response (Red Line)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Low Freq:</strong> +90° (+1.57 rad) phase lead</li>
                <li><strong>At Cutoff (fc):</strong> +45° (+0.785 rad)</li>
                <li><strong>High Freq:</strong> Approaches 0° (0 rad)</li>
                <li>Capacitor causes leading phase at low frequencies</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">The circuit functions as a <strong>high-pass filter</strong>. It blocks low-frequency signals (below 159 Hz) with significant attenuation while allowing high-frequency signals to pass through with minimal loss. The capacitor blocks DC and low frequencies, while passing AC signals above the cutoff frequency. The phase leads at low frequencies and approaches zero at high frequencies.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ch-card" style="background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;">
        <h2 style="color: #16a085;">Key Differences from Low-Pass Filter</h2>
        <ul style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
            <li><strong>Component arrangement:</strong> C in series, R to ground (reversed from LPF)</li>
            <li><strong>Frequency response:</strong> Passes HIGH frequencies, blocks LOW frequencies</li>
            <li><strong>Magnitude slope:</strong> +20 dB/decade (rising) vs -20 dB/decade (falling)</li>
            <li><strong>Phase:</strong> Starts at +90° and goes to 0° (vs 0° to -90° for LPF)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

